    <h1>Introduction to the Soar Cognitive Architecture</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">John E. Laird · 2022 · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2205.03854"><img src="/reading/arxiv.webp" alt="arxiv" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/> arXiv:2205.03854</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">The most complete symbolic cognitive architecture. Four memories, four learning modules, one decision cycle. Forty years of building the whole mind, one wall at a time.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>What Soar is</h2>

    <p>Soar is not a model. It is a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognitive_architecture"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>cognitive architecture</a>, a fixed set of mechanisms that an agent uses to perceive, decide, act, and learn across any domain. The architecture does not change per task. The knowledge does.</p>

    <p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allen_Newell"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Allen Newell</a> proposed in 1990 that cognitive science needed unified theories, not isolated models. Soar is the most sustained attempt to build one. It started in 1983 and has been continuously extended for four decades.</p>

